require us to face up to, and more effectively

43
00:04:32,270 --> 00:04:39,270
deal with, imperfection. There are multiple
reasons for, and dimensions of, this imperfection.

44
00:04:39,400 --> 00:04:44,699
A first clue came from one of the metaphors
covered in week 1: the more we know, the more

45
00:04:44,699 --> 00:04:49,969
we are aware of what we don't know. And of
course we can't know everything, let alone

46
00:04:49,969 --> 00:04:56,810
know all the things that we don't know. Ann
Kerwin's concept of unknown unknowns alerts

47
00:04:56,810 --> 00:05:03,389
us to the fact that there will also be unknowns
in complex problems that catch us by surprise.

48
00:05:03,389 --> 00:05:08,259
And in week 5 we learnt that there are problems
with rare outcomes where it is just not possible

49
00:05:08,259 --> 00:05:15,180
to have a high degree of certainty and that
also have imperfect outcomes therefore.

50
00:05:15,180 --> 00:05:18,900
The fact that complex problems are big and
that we often don't pay good attention to

51
00:05:18,900 --> 00:05:24,479
scoping is another source of imperfection.
We can't do everything and have to draw boundaries

52
00:05:24,479 --> 00:05:30,300
concentrating on what's feasible. That means
that aspects of the problem are ignored and

53
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:35,729
that's another source of imperfection. So
is the fact that there are no ways to integrate

54
00:05:35,729 --> 00:05:41,219
everything we know, let alone integrating
everything we don't know.

55
00:05:41,219 --> 00:05:46,330
These are all components of so-called "wicked"
problems, in other words problems that don't

56
00:05:46,330 --> 00:05:53,139
have straight-forward perfect solutions, so
imperfection is inbuilt in most complex problems.

